@NODE Install "Overview & Installation"

Please read this manual in its entirety before attempting to install or
use the emulation!  Any last-minute information and changes can be found
in the "Read Me First" file on the disk.

@{B}@{U}Overview@{UU}@{UB}

FUSION is a Macintosh 68K emulation.  Where differences exist between a
real Macintosh 68K computer and FUSION, they will be noted.  It is assumed
that the user is familiar with the Macintosh system and any applications
the user wishes to use.  If you are not familiar with the Macintosh, it is
suggested that you purchase "how to" books to learn.

The Macintosh computer has revolutionized the computer industry with its
strong points in user-friendliness and power-house software.  With programs
such as Adobe Photoshop, Adobe Illustrator, Aldus Freehand, Quark Express,
Fractal Painter, and countless others, it proves that even though the
Macintosh lacks the potential of the Amiga, it has some of the best
software for it ever written, making it almost a requirement in the
professional environment.

Since there is little chance these applications will be "ported" to the
Amiga, FUSION emulates the @{I}system@{UI} to allow users to utilize these tools
available for the Macintosh.

@{B}@{U}Emulation Requirements@{UU}@{UB}

To use FUSION, you need:

1 - @{B}Apple 256K/512K/1M ROMs from a 68K based Macintosh.@{UB}        @{"More Info" link Roms}

2 - @{B}Macintosh System 7.1 or newer System Software.@{UB}             @{"More Info" link MacSystem}

3 - @{B}A 68020/030/040/060 CPU.@{UB}                                   @{"More Info" link Cpu}

4 - @{B}At least 8 Megabytes of FAST memory.@{UB}                       @{"More Info" link Ram}

5 - @{B}At least 20 MBytes of harddrive space or a dedicated drive.@{UB}@{"More Info" link HDisk}

6 - @{B}AmigaOS v2.04 (Kickstart 37) or newer.@{UB}                     @{"More Info" link AmigaOS}

@{B}@{U}Making Backups@{UU}@{UB}

@{B}Before using the FUSION disk, please make a backup and place the original
in a safe place.@{UB}  Note: You are authorized to make a backup for your own
use.  The disk is unprotected and may be copied using any Amiga disk copier.

The software may not distributed in any form and any backups must be erased
if ownership of the emulation is transferred (i.e., it is sold).

@{B}@{U}Software Installation@{UU}@{UB}

@{I}A brief overview of the installation:@{UI}

1 - @{B}Insert the "FUSION" software disk into an Amiga disk drive.@{UB}

2 - @{B}Double-click on the disk's icon (this will open its window).@{UB}

3 - @{B}Double-click on the icon labeled "HardDisk_Installer."@{UB}

    Now the Amiga's "Installer" program will load and its
    window will open.

4 - @{B}Select the @{I}Proceed@{UI} button if you are ready, or @{I}Help...@{UI} if
    you need more help first.@{UB}

5 - @{B}Follow all the instructions the installer gives you.@{UB}

    The installer will ask you a question at the top of the
    window and provide a set of response buttons at the bottom
    of the window for you to select.

6 - @{B}When the installer has completed its installation and you
    are ready to test the software, turn off the computer, let it
    sit for 45sec to a minute, then switch it back on.@{UB}

    After installation, it is normal for the computer to reset
    itself once the first time the computer is turned on.  This
    is due to a program in the startup-sequence used to reserve
    some chip memory needed by the emulation.

@{B}@{U}Reserving Low Memory@{UU}@{UB}

The installer adds a line to the startup-sequence which reserves some chip
memory needed by the emulation.  The two programs which reserve memory are:

                              @{B}RsrvCold@{UB}

This program uses the ColdCapture and CoolCapture vectors in exec.library
to reserve the memory; some virus checkers will identify this as a virus.

RsrvCold has two switches which can be specified:

    F - put the capture code in fast memory.  The default is to place the
    code into chip memory.  Chip memory must be used with some accelerators.
    If you add this switch and the computer will not boot, remove it.

    O - reserve twice the normal amount of chip memory.  This will allow
    the use of a future revision of OxyPatcher with FUSION.

The switches are not case sensitive and may be specified in any order.

Examples:

      RsrvCold >NIL: -of
      RsrvCold >NIL: -f

                              @{B}RsrvWarm@{UB}

This program uses a resident structure to reserve the needed memory.

RsrvWarm has four switches which can be specified:

    F - put the resident structure in fast memory.  The default is to
    place the structure into chip memory.

    R - use an alternate method to rekick the computer.  Some computers
    will not boot to Workbench unless this switch is used.  If your
    computer will not boot after this line is added to the startup-
    sequence, try adding this switch.  Note: this switch forces RsrvWarm
    to always use chip memory; the F switch is ignored.

    S - split the first memory node into two pieces.  This is for use
    with the original version of the EMPLANT MAC emulation on A3000's
    running in 24bit memory mode.

    O - reserve twice the normal amount of chip memory.  This will allow
    the use of a future revision of OxyPatcher with FUSION.

Examples:

    RsrvWarm >NIL: -fo
    RsrvWarm >NIL: -ro
    RsrvWarm >NIL: -r
@ENDNODE Install
@NODE Roms "Macintosh ROMs"

FUSION needs 256K, 512K, or 1M ROMs from a 68K Macintosh for proper
operation.  PowerPC or old black&white Macintosh ROMs are not supported.

Computers known to have usable 256K ROMs are:
    MacII, MacIIx, MacIIcx, and the MacSE/030.

Computers known to have usable 512K ROMs are:
    MacIIci, MacIIsi, MacIIfx, LC, and LCII.

Computers known to have usable 1M ROMs are:
    Various Centris and Quadra systems.

This is by no means a complete list, but only meant for reference.  It is
recommended that 512K or 1M ROMs be used if you are planning to use MAC/OS
7.5 or newer.  The Display Manager in 7.5 and newer does not properly
handle 256K ROMs.  They will work, but display resolutions will not change
immediately, nor will display resolutions be listed correctly.  The type
of CPU in your Amiga has no bearing on the ROMs; 256K ROMs can be used
even with a 68060 processor.  Generally, Microcode Solutions recommends
512K ROMs be used for any system or cpu, unless you wish to use MacOS 8.
MacOS 8 requires the use of 1M ROMs.

ROMs are used in file format by FUSION.  A program is included with
FUSION to make this file on a real Macintosh; copy the file 'ROMUtil.hqx'
(located in your FUSION:Utils directory) onto a PC disk using CrossDOS on
your Amiga; then, insert the disk into the Macintosh (it must have PC
Exchange or something similar running on it to use PC disks).  There are
many Mac programs that will decode hqx files; one of the most common (and
available on the net) is StuffIt Expander; drop ROMUtil.hqx on StuffIt
Expander to obtain the program ROMUtil.  When ROMUtil is run, it displays
information about the machine it is on, including whether the ROMs are
usable.  Click on @{B}SAVE@{UB} to save the ROMs to a file.  Drag this file
back onto the PC disk and use CrossDOS to copy the ROM file into the FUSION
rom image drawer.  MAKE SURE that you do not have any filtering turned on
in the CrossDOS preferences!  You do not want to convert carriage returns
into linefeeds on a binary file!

@{B}It is @{I}illegal@{UI} to do this if you do not own the Macintosh, or
a set of the ROMs.@{UB}  ROMs can be purchased from a variety of
third-party Mac refurbishing centers.  Also, old Macintoshes such as the
MacIIci/si/lc can be purchased through the net and/or resellers for next
to nothing.
@ENDNODE Roms
@NODE MacSystem "Macintosh System Software"

FUSION needs Macintosh System Software to operate properly.  System 7.1
through System 8.1 are supported, but System 7.5.1 or newer is recommended
for a two main reasons:

1 - These systems are much more stable than 7.1.x or 7.5.0.

2 - These systems have added functionality used by FUSION.  Most
    notably, the Display Manager which let's the user switch
    resolutions on the fly, and virtual memory.  These features
    are also present and usable in 7.5.0, but 7.5.0 has various
    bugs which are fixed in later versions.

You may @{B}NOT@{UB} use System Software shipped with a Mac as that software is only
usable on @{I}that particular computer@{UI}.  You must have the generic software
usable by @{B}any@{UB} Macintosh.  This can be purchased from any store carrying
Macintosh software, or through mail-order companies.

When installing the software, boot off the Disk Tools disk.  Once it boots
up it will ask to format the harddrive/hardfile you selected under DEVICES
if it is not yet been formatted in Mac format.  This will erase any previous
information on the harddrive/hardfile, so be sure you have not selected
your Workbench or Work drive!  Once it has been formatted as Mac format,
run the Install program if you are using a CD, or boot the Install 1 disk
if your are using floppies.  Do @{B}NOT@{UB} choose Easy Install!  You must select
Custom Installation, click on the triangle next to System, and choose
@{I}System For Any Macintosh@{UI}.  Then select Extension and Control Panels; you
may also want some of the other selections depending on how you plan on
using your system (e.g., select Network Software if you plan on using Mac
networking).  If you do not select @{I}System For Any Macintosh@{UI}, the software
installed will probably not have the resources necessary to boot under the
emulation.
@ENDNODE MacSystem
@NODE Cpu "Amiga CPUs Supported"

FUSION will work on any Amiga equipped with a 68020, 030, 040, or 060 cpu,
however, best performance requires an 040 or 060 with MMU and FPU.

If your CPU does not have an MMU, you will not be able to use Virtual
Memory, refreshed video drivers (other than those with QD in the name)
will be substantially slower, and the Macintosh will be slower on OS
traps.  If your CPU does not have an FPU,  any floating point done
by the Macintosh will be slow, and Macintosh programs requiring an FPU
will not run.

A 68020 requires a 68851 for MMU support, and a 68881 or 68882 for FPU
support.  A 68030 requires a 68881 or 68882 for FPU support.  There are
low-cost versions of the 68030/040 produced without an MMU; these are
referred to as EC chips.  They must be replaced with non-EC versions if
MMU support is desired.  A low cost version of the 040, the 68LC040, has
no FPU; this must be replaced by a normal 68040 for FPU support.

The 68060 is fully supported, but under MacOS 8, Finder is no longer
SuperScalar compatible.  System 7.5.x is SuperScalar compatible and is
therefore slightly faster.  The difference is not that great; Speedometer
3.23 gives a cpu rating of 53 on the Phase 5 Mark II 50Mhz 060 card under
7.5.5 with SuperScalar on; the same card gets 49 under MacOS 8.
SuperScalar does not affect floating point operations, only integer
operations.
@ENDNODE Cpu
@NODE Ram "Amiga RAM Requirements"

Modern Macintosh System Software and Applications need all the RAM they
can get (e.g., Netscape requires 16 MBytes just for itself).  A standard
installation of System 7.5.x with the extensions on will use around 4 MB.
The emulation can be run in less than 8MBytes, but it is not very useful
(especially for professional use).  RAM is cheap right now, @{B}BUY SOME!@{UB}
Virtual Memory can be used to simulate more RAM, but it will be slower
than having physical memory.  Also, some programs will not run with virtual
memory active.  Games in particular either won't run or run horribly slow
with virtual memory.  However, if you have a SCSI-II drive and are trying
to run PhotoShop with 100-200 MBytes, virtual memory may be just the thing.

Some old programs/games are not completely 32bit clean.  This generally
means they won't work on most systems.  However, FUSION allows a pseudo-
24bit mode to be setup if you have an MMU.  This uses space in the Zorro
II region of the Amiga, so any Zorro II RAM or video cards will interfere,
reducing the amount of RAM you may select in Pseudo-24bit mode.

For greatest speed, the RAM you select for the emulation should be RAM
directly accessible to the CPU (i.e., on the accelerator).  It is usually
given the highest priority and shows first in the RAM list.
@ENDNODE Ram
@NODE HDisk "Hard Drive Requirements"

FUSION should be installed on your main Amiga Work partition.  It uses less
than 1 MByte of space.

The Macintosh will need at least 20 MBytes; in reality, you will find that
you need 100-400 MBytes of space for typical operation.  Small amounts (20
to 50 MBytes) can be setup as hardfiles; larger amounts can also be setup
as hardfiles, but this is not recommended.  Larger amounts should be setup
as dedicated partitions or hard drives.

The speed of hardfiles may be increased by adding AmigaDOS buffers to the
drive the hardfile is on.  E.G., if your hardfile is on DH1:, you should
put the following line in your user-startup file:

	@{B}C:AddBuffers MSHF: 1000@{UB}

This adds 1000 buffers to MSHF (this is the hardfile assignment path); more
than 2000 will not make the hardfile much faster.  Adding fewer than 256
buffers will not speed up the hardfile very much.  The recommended range is
500 to 2000.  Remember that each buffer uses .5KBytes of space; 1000 buffers
will take 500KBytes of memory.
@ENDNODE HDisk
@NODE AmigaOS

AmigaOS 2.04 or newer is required for FUSION to operate properly.  If you
have not upgraded from 1.3, now is the time!  AmigaOS 3.x is needed if you
plan to use Cybergraphics or Picasso96 video cards with the emulation.

Any Amiga dealer carries AmigaOS 3.1 upgrade ROMs and Workbench software.
This version of the AmigaOS is highly recommended.
@ENDNODE AmigaOS
@NODE Setup "Emulation Setup Window"

                @{B}@{U}Setting Up & Starting the Emulation@{UU}@{UB}

FUSION may be run from a CLI or from Workbench.  When it is run from a CLI,
an optional switch, -s, may be used.  This switch causes FUSION to skip the
Emulation Setup Window and start up the emulation directly.  This should
not be done the first time FUSION is run as there are a few options that
need to be configured.  If this switch is not used, or if FUSION is run from
Workbench, the Emulation Setup Window is opened on Workbench.  Another
switch, -c, may be used to automatically load another configuration file
than the default.  The filename follows the switch.  The switch -h shows
a help message to the console about the FUSION switches.

When the emulation is run, and no configuration file is found, a license
agreement for FUSION is displayed.  The program will not continue to the
configuration display unless you agree to the license.  By agreeing with
the license, you are bound by it stipulations.

@{B}Emulation Setup Window@{UB}

        A cycle gadget is used to determine which configuration option
gadgets are accessible.  The available options are:

	@{"Memory       " link MemoryOpt}			@{I}Select Memory and Mapping.@{UI}
	@{"Video        " link VideoOpt}			@{I}Select Video Driver(s).@{UI}
	@{"Floppy       " link FloppyOpt}			@{I}Select Floppy Drive(s).@{UI}
	@{"Devices      " link DeviceOpt}			@{I}Select HardDrives/HardFiles.@{UI}
	@{"Ports        " link PortOpt}			@{I}Select Serial/Parallel Drivers.@{UI}
	@{"ROM Images   " link ROMOpt}			@{I}Select ROM Image.@{UI}
	@{"Sound        " link SoundOpt}			@{I}Select Sound Output/Input.@{UI}
	@{"Peripherals  " link PeriOpt}			@{I}Select CD-ROM/ADB/SCSI/Network.@{UI}
	@{"Advanced     " link AdvancedOpt}			@{I}Select Hardware/Machine/Priorities.@{UI}
	@{"Configuration" link ConfigOpt}			@{I}Load/Save Configuration.@{UI}

Once all the options are set they way you prefer, you may click on the
button @{B}Start Emulator@{UB} (or press S on the keyboard).

        The Emulation Setup Window closes and the emulation attempts to
setup the MAC system using the specified options.  If an error occurs,
a message will be displayed and the Emulation Setup Window will be re-
opened.  You must correct the error before attempting to start the emulator
again.
@ENDNODE Setup
@NODE MemoryOpt "Select Memory and Mapping"

                        @{B}@{U}Memory Options Setup@{UU}@{UB}

When the Memory Options configuration is selected,  a listview (window with
selectable data inside it) shows the blocks of memory available in the
system; for each block, the priority, type, speed (in MBytes/sec), base
address, and amount free are displayed.  In most cases, the highest priority
block will also be the fastest; you want to select 32bit fast memory for the
emulation.  By default, FUSION picks the highest priority block unless it is
less than 8MBytes and there also exists another block which is larger; three
quarters of this block is selected for the MAC main memory.  Click on another
block to select it in place of the currently highlighted block.  The slider
changes the amount of memory taken from the block.  Remember to leave some
memory for the video driver and ROM image.  If you are not sure about the
memory requirements for the rest of the emulation, configure everything else
first, then return to the memory option configuration.

@{B}Memory Options@{UB}

Click on the @{B}Memory Options@{UB} button, or press M to bring up the Memory
Mapping cycle gadget, Virtual Base cycle gadget, KickStart Remap cycle
gadget, and the Memory Test button.  @{B}If you do not have an MMU, you MUST
select @{U}No MMU@{UU} with the Memory Mapping cycle gadget!@{UB}  There is no way for
software to properly detect whether or not an MMU is present, so we rely
on the user to tell FUSION when it is.  If you select any other setting,
the Amiga @{B}WILL@{UB} crash at some point.

If you do have an MMU, you may select from the following:

	@{B}No MMU@{UB} - You may choose not to use the MMU if you so desire.
Not using the MMU will make the emulation slower.

	@{B}Normal@{UB} - This allows FUSION to remap a few things to gain
10% to 50% in speed compared to No MMU.  Refreshed video is accelerated
considerably as well.

	@{B}Pseudo 24@{UB} - This uses the MMU to remap the MAC main memory
into the Zorro II address space.  Some older MAC programs (particularly
games), are not completely 32bit clean; i.e., they will not run if the
program loads into memory above a certain address.  Pseudo 24 mode maps
the MAC memory into an area below this point.  The maximum amount of memory
you can select in this mode depends on whether you have any Zorro II cards
with memory on them; examples of these include: a Zorro II video card like
the Picasso II, or a 2091 SCSI card with memory.  If you have a card like
this, you will have to experiment with different amounts of memory or
remove the card.  If you don't have one, the maximum memory you can select
is 9.5MBytes minus the length of the ROM image.  If you only have 1MByte of
chip memory (on an A2000, e.g.), you can add 1MByte to the previous figure.

	@{B}Virtual Memory@{UB} - This mode is used in conjunction with MAC's
virtual memory manager to allow the user to simulate more memory within the
emulation.  You must have System 7.5.0 or newer, and as much space on your
harddrive/hardfile as you wish to have memory.  When you select this mode,
the Virtual Base becomes active; the default (Low Region) is suitable for
most Amigas, and allows for up to 95MBytes of virtual memory.  If you have
memory at $2000000 (some 040/060 cards) or at $7000000 (mother board memory
on A3000/A4000), you are restricted to 63MBytes, maximum.  To allow for more
virtual memory, toggle the Virtual Base gadget to High Region.  This allows
for a maximum of 767MBytes of virtual memory, but requires 2MBytes of memory
for the larger tables needed.  The amount of memory selected on the Amiga
then becomes the amount of @{I}page frame space@{UI} available to the MAC.
Virtual memory runs faster with more page frame space.  To activate virtual
memory, you must run the Memory Control Panel on the MAC side, turn on
virtual memory, select a drive, select how much space to use on the drive,
then restart the MAC via the pull-down menu.

FUSION now merges with an existing MMU table, as long as it is compatible.
The MMU maps setup by existing 040/060 libraries are compatible with FUSION.
An incompatible MMU map will be replaced by FUSION the first time it is run.

If you set the Memory Mapping to anything other than No MMU, you may set
the KickStart Remap cycle gadget to the following:

	@{B}None@{UB}  - Does not try to remap the Amiga ROMs into memory.
This saves space when memory is tight.

	@{B}Normal@{UB} - Remaps the Amiga ROMs into fast memory.  With an
accelerated Amiga with memory on the accelerator, this mode is faster. The
first time FUSION runs, this will take 512K from the Amiga unless the ROM
is already remapped to Fast RAM.

	@{B}SuperKick A3000@{UB} - Is @{I}required@{UI} on Super-KickStart A3000s.
These were the original A3000s which booted KickStart off the hard drive.
When you turn on your A3000 and see a dark gray screen with orange text
reading "Loading Kickstart 2.x", you have a Super-KickStart A3000.

	@{B}Memory Test@{UB} - click on this button to do a non-destructive test of
the currently selected memory node.  The address of the node appears above
the button.  The amount of memory tested is equal to the amount selected.
@ENDNODE MemoryOpt
@NODE VideoOpt "Select Video Driver(s)"

                        @{B}@{U}Video Options Setup@{UU}@{UB}

When the Video Options configuration is selected, two listviews display
what drivers are available, and which have been selected.  Up to six may
be selected at a time.  Each controls a screen available to the MAC; e.g.,
if 'amiRefresh' is selected twice, two Amiga refreshed display screens are
opened for the MAC to use.  Please remember that video drivers use memory,
so only select multiple screens if you need them; most people should never
need more than one.  If you are using 512K or 1M ROMs with System 7.5.0
or newer, FUSION supports changing the screen resolution on the fly. This
is part of the Display Manager in 7.5+.  You do not have to restart the
MAC to get the new resolution as with older Systems.  This greatly reduces
the need for more than one screen for most people.

At least one driver must be selected for the MAC emulation to run!

Click on the @{B}Filter Options@{UB} button, or press F to get a set of
check boxes which limit which drivers will be displayed in the Available
Drivers listview.  All Drivers allows you to see all drivers,including
those which will not work on your System.  If you try to select a driver
that will not work on your System, you get the driver setup and
information controls, but the driver is not selected.  Selecting Show
Direct Drivers and/or Show Refreshed Drivers shows direct and/or refreshed
drivers, respectively, in the Available Drivers listview.

If you click on the name of a driver in the Available Drivers listview,
the driver will be selected for use with the emulation.  This is indicated
by showing the driver name in the Selected Drivers listview.  If you
SHIFT-click (hold down the SHIFT key while clicking on an entry) on the
name of a driver, detailed information about the driver will be displayed,
but the driver will NOT be selected.  This allows you to view information
about the various drivers so you can make a decision of what driver would
work best for your setup.

If you select a driver in the Selected Drivers listview, you get the
driver setup and information controls.  The driver name, version, and
memory used are displayed.  If the driver is a direct driver (i.e., the
MAC draws straight into the display), the QDXL cycle gadget allows you
to enable blitter accelerated video.  If the driver is a refreshed driver
(i.e., the MAC draws to RAM and the Amiga converts the data), the Refresh
Rate cycle gadget lets you change the initial rate at which the display
is updated.  Both of these settings may be changed while the MAC is
running using the Video Control option from the FUSION Control Window.
If the driver you have selected supports multiple monitor IDs, then the
gadget will be unghosted.  This option allows for using more than one
video board with either Cybergraphics or Picasso96.  Unless each board
has its own monitor ID, there is no way for the emulation to know which
board should be used in a multi-board setup.  If you only have one video
board, just leave the entry set to 00000000.  Click on the @{B}More
Information@{UB} button, or press I to get a listview with a description
of the selected driver.

If you SHIFT-click on a driver name in the Selected Drivers listview, that
entry will be removed from the list.

@{B}Currently Available Drivers@{UB}

                              @{B}Direct@{UB}

	@{B}amiDirectXL@{UB} - This driver opens a black and white Amiga screen
which the MAC can draw into directly.  Since the MAC uses chunky video
and the Amiga uses planar video, this is the only depth that can be done
directly on the Amiga video.  The Amiga blitter is supported for accel-
erated MAC video.  Please note that the blitter will be faster only if
you have an 020.  The 68030/040/060 CPUs are capable of much greater speed
than the blitter.

	@{B}cgxDirectXL@{UB} - This driver opens screens the MAC can draw into
directly on any Cybergraphics compatible card.  If you do not have an MMU,
only 256 colors are supported.  The PicassoIV and PiccoloSD64 both support
direct thousands mode with an MMU.  The CyberVision and CyberVision 3D
both support direct thousands and millions modes with an MMU.  All other
cards only support 256 colors.  Cards with blitters can be used to accel-
erate the MAC video.  A PicassoIV or CyberVision(3D) both outperform most
MACs in video tests!  Due to limitations in the CyberGraphics software,
multiple cgxDirectXL screens are not recommended.  In fact, having Work-
bench on the CyberGraphics card at the same time can/will cause some
interference between the two screens.  This will not change until the
CyberGraphics software allows video card memory and offscreen fast ram on
4K boundaries (like Picasso96).

	@{B}p96DirectXL@{UB} - This driver opens screens the MAC can draw into
directly on any Picasso96 compatible card.  If you do not have an MMU,
only 256 colors are supported.  The PicassoIV and PiccoloSD64 both support
direct thousands mode with an MMU.  The CyberVision supports direct thous-
ands and millions modes with an MMU.  There is no CyberVision3D driver for
Picasso96 at this time.  All other cards only support 256 colors.  Cards
with blitters can be used to accelerate the MAC video.

                             @{B}Refreshed@{UB}

	@{B}amiQDDRefreshed@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver designed for those
without an MMU.  It uses QuickDraw damage rectangles to update the MAC
display.  This approach does not work with programs which draw directly to
the screen, bypassing QuickDraw.  It supports 16 colors on OCS/ECS Amigas,
and 16 color, 256 color, thousands, and millions modes on AGA Amigas.
It is recommended that you turn off the MAC menu bar clock with any QD
driver, as it will cause the entire screen to be refreshed each time the
clock is updated.

	@{B}amiRefresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver designed for those with
an MMU.  It uses the MMU to accelerate the refresh process, and works with
any MAC program.  It supports 16 colors on OCS/ECS Amigas, and 16 color,
256 color, thousands, and millions modes on AGA Amigas.

	@{B}CD32_DQDRefresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver designed for CD32
owners.  It uses QuickDraw damage rectangles along with a periodic full-
screen update.  If no damage rectangles are found within ten refresh
periods, the entire screen is updated.  This makes it usable with programs
which bypass QuickDraw.  This driver also allocates the MAC video memory
from chip memory to maximize the amount of fast memory left for the MAC;
it also uses the AKIKO to speed the chunky to planar conversion.  Only
16 color and 256 color modes are supported.  See note above about the MAC
menu bar clock.

	@{B}CD32_QDDRefresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver designed for CD32
owners.  It uses QuickDraw damage rectangles to update the display.  It
will not work with programs that bypass QuickDraw.  This driver also al-
locates the MAC video memory from chip memory to maximize the amount of
fast memory left for the MAC; it also uses the AKIKO to speed the chunky
to planar conversion.  Only 16 color and 256 color modes are supported.
See note above about the MAC menu bar clock.

	@{B}cgxRefresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver that allows for 16 color,
256 color, thousands, and millions modes on all Cybergraphics supported
cards.  Please note that it uses 4MBytes of RAM and works best with an
MMU.  If you do not have an MMU, set the refresh rate to 15FPS or lower
for better speed.

	@{B}grfRefresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver that allows for 16 color
and 256 color modes on AGA Amigas with the Graffiti Module.  It works best
with an MMU; if you do not have an MMU, set the refresh rate to 15FPS or
lower for better speed.  Please note that the Graffiti driver only works
with AGA machines.  This is because the Graffiti hardware requires an Amiga
display that is twice the width of the actual display, and non-AGA machines
are not capable of displaying 1280 widths (giving you a 640 wide Graffiti
display).

	@{B}p96Refresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver that allows for 16 color,
256 color, thousands, and millions modes on all Picasso96 supported cards.
Please note that it uses 4MBytes of RAM and works best with an MMU.  If
you do not have an MMU, set the refresh rate to 15FPS or lower for better
speed.

	@{B}rtnRefresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver that allows for 16 color,
256 color, thousands, and millions modes on a Retina Z2 or Retina Z3 (it is
recommended that you use Picasso96 or Cybergraphics with the Retina Z3).
Please note that it uses 4MBytes of RAM and works best with an MMU.  If
you do not have an MMU, set the refresh rate to 15FPS or lower for better
speed.  This driver requires that the RetinaEMU be active, and the DEFAULT
output to be set to RETINA.  Make sure that the DEFAULT entry size variables
are checked, indicating auto-sizing; this allows for automatically changing
the display size to fill the entire screen when resolutions change.

	@{B}wbwRefresh@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver that displays the MAC
screen in a window on Workbench.  It will work on an Amiga without a video
card, but is not recommended because of the speed.  Workbench must be set
to 16 colors to allow 16 color or 256 color displays.  Please note that in
256 color mode, most of the colors are approximated.  Workbench set to
256 colors gives a better 256 color display.  If you have Workbench on a
video card in 256 color mode, you may use 16 color and 256 color mode;
this is the fastest mode for this driver.  If you have Workbench set to
15/16/24/32 bit depth, the MAC millions mode is allowed.  Please note that
if you are in 15/16 bit depth, the MAC millions display will be approx-
imated.  16 color and 256 color modes are allowed, but are slower than if
the card was set to 256 color depth.  You must click both the right and
left mouse buttons at the same time, or click the middle button of a three
button mouse to deselect the MAC window.  The window may be dragged or
resized.  If the window is smaller than the MAC display, the contents of
the window scroll when the MAC mouse hits the window border.  Workbench
3.0 or later is required to use this driver.

	@{B}p96PIP@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver that displays the MAC
screen in a Picasso96 Picture-n-Picture window on Workbench.  The window
can be resized larger (not smaller), and this is handled in hardware by
the video board.  Please note that only the PicassoIV supports this
feature.

	@{B}cgxVideo@{UB} - This is a refreshed driver that displays the MAC
screen in a Cybergraphics overlay (Picture-n-Picture) window on Workbench.
The window can be resized smaller or larger, and this is handled in hardware
by the video board.  Please note that only the Cybervision64/3D supports this
feature.

@ENDNODE VideoOpt
@NODE FloppyOpt "Select Floppy Drive(s)"

                       @{B}Floppy Options Setup@{UB}

When the Floppy Options configuration is selected, two cycle gadgets are
used to select which floppy(s) the MAC may use.  The default is to select
DF0: for the first MAC floppy, and none for the second.  The cycle gadget
allows the selection of any available floppy and AMIA (if present).  The
buttons are used to determine if only the MAC has access to its selected
floppy(s), or if it must share the floppy(s) with the Amiga.  If exclusive
is selected (default setting), you will get a BUSY icon on Workbench for
each selected floppy.  If not selected, conflicts may arise between the
Amiga and the emulation over access to the floppy.
@ENDNODE FloppyOpt
@NODE DeviceOpt "Select Hard Drive(s) and/or Hard File(s)"

                       @{B}Device Options Setup@{UB}

When the Device Options configuration is selected, two listviews show the
Usable Devices and the Selected Devices.  Click on a device name in the
left listview to select it.  SHIFT-Click on the device name the left
listview to view detailed information about the device.  Clicking on a name
in the right listview shows the device name, size of the device, and
the current format of the device (AmigaDOS, Macintosh, PC, or unknown).
Also, there are several device options:

	@{B}Force Write Protect@{UB} prevents the emulation from being able to
write this device.

	@{B}DMA Restrictions@{UB} is needed for people using DMA SCSI drives on
their Amiga which cannot write to ANY block of memory; e.g., a 2091 SCSI
card cannot write directly to memory on a Warp Engine 68040 accelerator
card.  If you deselect this and have trouble formatting a harddrive or in-
stalling software, you must turn on this option @{B}AND REFORMAT AND REINSTALL
ALL SOFTWARE ON THAT DRIVE!@{UB}.  If you had the option off and had ANY problem
because of it, the information on the drive has been badly corrupted and
cannot be salvaged.  If in doubt, just leave this option ON (default set-
ting); at worst, it will only slow drive access about 5% to 25%.  If you
have selected Virtual Memory in the Memory Options Setup, DMA Restrictions
are forced on @{I}ALWAYS@{UI}, regardless of how you may set it here.  This is
necessary because virtual memory does not really exist and cannot be written
to by anything other than the CPU.

	@{B}Removable Media@{UB} allows the Mac to eject the volume.  The
volume may be remounted by clicking on @{B}Remount Ejected@{UB} after clicking
on @{B}Device Control@{UB} button of the Emulation Control Window.  If you remove
the volume from the Amiga and insert another, it will automatically remount
the volume.  This option would be selected if you were trying to use a
removable media device with the emulation; e.g., a SyQuest drive, a ZIP
drive, CatWeasel, etc.  CD-ROMS should NOT be selected here, but rather in
@{"CD-ROM Setup" link CDROMSetup} in @{B}Peripherals.@{UB}

	@{B}Skip Validation@{UB} allows the Mac to boot from a partition
that was not properly shut down.  If your machine boots to the 'smiley
Mac' and then resets, and repeats this over and over, you will need to
make sure that this option IS selected (default is selected).  If this
does not cure your problem, you will need to re-install the System software.

The @{B}Create DOSDriver@{UB} button will create a DOSDriver for the selected
device.  This is not necessary for using the device with the emulation.
If you don't know what you would do with a DOSDriver, DON'T CREATE ONE!

SHIFT-Clicking on the right listview will remove the device from use
by the emulation, and return the name back in the left listview.

	@{B}HardFile Setup@{UB} takes you to the HardFile Setup controls.  Here,
you may select the size of the hardfile, and create or remove hardfiles.
The size of the hardfile is set as the number of MBytes you wish.  Then
click on the @{B}Create@{UB} button, or press C, to bring up a requester asking
where you wish it to be stored and under what name.  If you wish to delete
a hardfile, click on the @{B}Remove@{UB} button, or press R, to bring up a requester
asking which hardfile to delete.  A hardfile is denoted in the listviews
by an asterisk (*) in front of the name.
@ENDNODE DeviceOpt
@NODE PortOpt "Select Serial, Parallel, or Hardware Drivers"

                        @{B}Ports Options Setup@{UB}

When the Ports Option configuration is selected, you get controls for
setting the two standard Mac serial ports, A and B.  If you have either
an @{B}EMPLANT@{UB} or an @{B}A-MaxII+@{UB} card, you may select the card to be used for
that port; no device driver or unit is required for this setting.  If
you select @{B}NONE@{UB} for the port, the port will not be available from the
Mac side.  Two other settings are available:

	@{B}Serial@{UB} - You must select some kind of Amiga serial device driver
and set the proper unit number.  This allows the Mac to use any Amiga
serial port as a Mac serial port.  The built-in Amiga serial port is
@{B}serial.device unit 0@{UB}.  Please note: 060 accelerated Amigas have problems
using serial.device; we use BaudBandit.device for serial on our Phase 5
060 equiped Amiga.

	@{B}Parallel@{UB} - You must select some kind of Amiga parallel device
driver and the proper unit number.  This allows the Mac to use any Amiga
parallel port @{I}with the appropriate software@{UI}.  To use a printer attached
to an Amiga parallel port,  you need software that sends data one way
only in the appropriate format.  PowerPrint from GDT Softworks (avail-
able in any Mac mail-order catalog) is an exceptional set of printer
drivers fully tested under FUSION.  The built-in Amiga parallel port is
@{B}parallel.device unit 0@{UB}.

Either port may be set to serial or parallel, but most Mac applications
expect a modem (serial) to be at port A, and a printer (parallel) to be
at port B.  You can still use either the EMPLANT or A-Max card to do
LocalTalk even if you redirect both ports A and B.
@ENDNODE PortOpt
@NODE ROMOpt "Select ROM Image"

                      @{B}ROM Image Options Setup@{UB}

When the ROM Image Option configuration is selected, you get a string
gadget which holds the name of the selected ROM image, and a GetFile
button to bring up a requester to select a ROM image.  Once a ROM image
has been selected, the type, size and checksum are then displayed.  If
a ROM image does not seem to work with FUSION, write down this infor-
mation and tell us about it.  Although FUSION has been tested on many
different ROMs, there are bound to be a few we haven't seen.

@{"Macintosh ROMs" link Roms} has more information on ROM images.
@ENDNODE ROMOpt
@NODE SoundOpt "Select Sound Output and Input"

                        @{B}Sound Options Setup@{UB}

When the Sound Option configuration is selected, a cycle gadget selects
the following modes for Audio output from the Mac:

	@{B}None@{UB} - This mode prevents the Mac from generating any audio.
Only useful if you need to use audio on the Amiga while using the Mac
and do not have an audio card.

	@{B}Amiga@{UB} - This is the default mode; it uses Paula to generate
stereo 8bit audio from the Mac.  You would use this if you do not have
an audio card, or if you do not like how much CPU time AHI uses.

	@{B}AHI@{UB} - If you have AHI available, this selection uses the best
mode available under AHI to generate stereo 16bit audio from the MAC.
If you do not have an audio card, AHI will generate 14bit audio using
Paula; this mode has no volume control.  You would use this if you need
to use CD quality audio on the Mac side, or have an audio card and need
to use the Amiga audio while using the Mac.  Please note that AHI uses
about 20% of the available CPU time.

The Startup Sound cycle gadget allows the selection of the MAC startup
sound.  Five startup sounds are available; the startup sound may be turned
off by selecting None.
@ENDNODE SoundOpt
@NODE PeriOpt "Select Peripheral Devices and Drivers"

                     @{B}Peripherals Options Setup@{UB}

When the Peripherals Option configuration is selected, four buttons are
available to configure the peripheral devices:

	@{"CD-ROM " link CDROMSetup}		@{I}Select a CD-ROM device.@{UI}
	@{"ADB    " link ADBSetup}		@{I}Select a mouse/keyboard driver.@{UI}
	@{"SCSI   " link SCSISetup}		@{I}Select hardware SCSI interface.@{UI}
	@{"Network" link NetworkSetup}		@{I}Select an EtherNet device.@{UI}

The only one of these that @{I}must@{UI} be set is ADB, and it is set by default
to the standard ADB driver.
@ENDNODE PeriOpt
@NODE CDROMSetup "CD-ROM Setup"

                           @{B}CD-ROM Setup@{UB}

The @{B}CD-ROM Type@{UB} cycle gadget tells FUSION how to use the CD-ROM:

	@{B}None@{UB} - No CD-ROM is selected.  This is the default setting.

	@{B}HFS/PC@{UB} - The CD-ROM is selected and will try to read both Mac
and PC formatted CDs.  The Device Driver string gadget holds the name of
the device used to access the CD-ROM; type the name in or use the GetFile
button if the device is a file in the DEVS: drawer.  The Unit string
gadget holds the unit number of the CD-ROM.  Typical CD-ROM selections
will be like @{B}scsi.device unit 6@{UB}, or @{B}warpdrive.device unit 0@{UB}.

	@{B}HFS Only@{UB} - The CD-ROM is selected and will try to read the Mac
portion of dual format CD-ROMs.  Use this setting if you have a dual
format CD that won't show the Mac side when using HFS/PC.

	@{B}PC Only@{UB} - The CD-ROM is selected and will try to read the PC
portion of dual format CD-ROMs. Use this setting if you have a dual format
CD and wish to see the PC side.

The @{B}Cache Size@{UB} cycle gadget selects the amount of memory to use to
buffer data from the CD-ROM.  For slower CD-ROMs (single/double speed),
use smaller cache sizes so that the CD-ROM doesn't spend so much time on
unnecessary cache filling.  Use larger sizes for faster CD-ROMs.

The @{B}Memory Type@{UB} cycle gadget selects the type of memory allocated for
the cache.  @{B}ANY@{UB} is suitable for most systems, but if you have
a problem reading CDs at all, try selecting @{B}CHIP@{UB}.

The @{B}Boot Priority@{UB} cycle gadget selects whether or not the CD-ROM
drive should be bootable.  Setting the gadget to @{B}FIRST@{UB} tells the
system to attempt to boot from the CD-ROM drive BEFORE any other device.
Setting the gadget to @{B}LAST@{UB} will not attempt to boot the system from
the CD-ROM drive.
@ENDNODE CDROMSetup
@NODE ADBSetup "Mouse and Keyboard Driver Setup"

                 @{B}ADB Mouse & Keyboard Driver Setup@{UB}

The @{B}ADB Type@{UB} cycle gadget select between two modes:

	@{B}Hardware@{UB} - This mode looks directly at the Amiga hardware for
the mouse position and buttons.

	@{B}Software@{UB} - This mode uses RELPOINTER messages for the mouse
position and BUTTON messages for the mouse buttons.  This allows the use
of Amiga graphics tablets as the Mac mouse.

	Both modes use messages for the keys.  A program like MacJoy or
MacJoyPad may be used to remap Amiga joystick movements and buttons into
Mac keys for use with Mac games.

The software driver @{I}must@{UI} be set!  There are two drivers currently
available:

	@{B}Std_ADB@{UB} - This driver is used on all keyboards that use the US,
UK, or Canadian layout keymaps.

	@{B}ISO_ADB@{UB} - This driver is used with keyboards that use the inter-
national keys (e.g., German keyboards).

The keys are mapped to equivalent Mac keys with the following exceptions:

	- F11 through F15 are not mapped.

	- The separate Home, End, PgUp and PgDn keys are not mapped.

	- Left Amiga - N and Left Amiga - M are reserved for Amiga screen
	control.  Use the Right Amiga key for these two combinations on
	the Mac side.

	- If you hold the Left Shift key while pressing either Left Amiga -
	N or Left Amiga - M, the Mac will be suspended.  This stops the
	Mac completely, leaving all CPU time available to the Amiga.
@ENDNODE ADBSetup
@NODE SCSISetup "Hardware SCSI Setup"

                        @{B}Hardware SCSI Setup@{UB}

This setup has been completely reworked; Amiga SCSI interfaces may now be
used from the MAC side when properly setup here.

The SCSI ID cycle gadget determines what MAC SCSI ID is currently being
setup; all the other gadgets refer to this ID number; i.e., as you change
the ID cycle gadget, all the other gadgets change to show that particular
ID's settings.  Up to seven device IDs are available.

The SCSI Hardware cycle gadget determines how the ID will be handled:

@{B}None@{UB} - The MAC will ignore this device ID. This speeds up a scan of the
SCSI bus from the MAC side.

@{B}Emulated@{UB} - The MAC will use an Amiga SCSI device specified by the Device
Driver string gadget and the Unit string gadget.  E.G., to use unit 4
of the WarpEngine SCSI, set Device Driver to "warpdrive.device" and Unit
to "4".  Please note, the SCSI ID gadget does not need to match Unit.
The Transfer cycle gadget selects the method of data transfer.  Select
"Direct" for direct transfers to/from the MAC memory; this is the fastest
method.  Some SCSI cards cannot do this and must be set to "Buffer"; the
SCSI card transfers data to/from a buffer which is emptied/filled by the
cpu.  This method is forced into effect while Virtual Memory is active.

@{B}EMPLANT@{UB} - This is available only if you have an EMPLANT card with the
SCSI option and have set the Emulation Hardware gadget in @{"Advanced" link AdvancedOpt} to
"EMPLANT Board".  The unit selected on the EMPLANT card is the same as
the SCSI ID.
@ENDNODE SCSISetup
@NODE NetworkSetup "EtherNet Setup"

                          @{B}EtherNet Setup@{UB}

If you have an EtherNet card in your Amiga, you can use it from the Mac
for EtherTalk if you enter the device name in the @{B}Ethernet Device Driver@{UB}
string (or select it using the GetFile button), and the unit number in
the @{B}Unit@{UB} string gadget.
@ENDNODE NetworkSetup
@NODE AdvancedOpt "Select Hardware, MachineID, and Priorities"

                      @{B}Advanced Options Setup@{UB}

When the Advanced Option configuration is selected, two cycle gadgets
allow the selection of the Emulation Hardware and the Machine Emulation.

Selections for @{B}Emulation Hardware@{UB} are:

	@{B}Amiga Chipset@{UB} - If you don't have an EMPLANT or A-MaxII+ card,
this will be the only selection.  It uses resources in the Amiga to em-
ulate specific hardware on the Mac.

	@{B}EMPLANT Board@{UB} - If you have an EMPLANT card, this is the default
selection.  It uses resources on the EMPLANT to emulate specific hardware
on the Mac.  Allows standard Mac serial and SCSI (as long as your EMPLANT
has the serial and SCSI options).  If you change the setting to the Amiga
Chipset, you will not be able to use the EMPLANT's serial or SCSI.

	@{B}AMAX II+ Board@{UB} - If you have an A-Max II+/IV card, and don't
have an EMPLANT card, this is the default selection.  If you have an
EMPLANT card as well, you may select AMAX, but it won't be the default.
It uses resources on the A-Max card to emulate specific Mac hardware.
When selected, you can select the serial ports for use with the Mac
and use LocalTalk.

Selections for @{B}Machine Emulation@{UB} are:

	@{B}Mac II@{UB}		A 15MHz 020 Color Mac.
	@{B}Mac IIx@{UB}		A 15Mhz 030 Color Mac.
	@{B}Mac IIci@{UB}	A 25Mhz 030 Color Mac.
	@{B}Mac IIfx@{UB}	A 40Mhz 030 Color Mac.
	@{B}Quadra 900@{UB}	A 25Mhz 040 Color Mac.
	@{B}Quadra 950@{UB}	A 33Mhz 040 Color Mac.

These make @{I}no difference what-so-ever@{UI} to the performance of the emulation;
a 40MHz 040 will still perform like a 40MHz 040 with the Mac II selection.
The only reason for this gadget is that there are some Mac programs that
look at the machine ID and will not work on certain Macs.  This gadget
allows you to set the machine ID as you wish.

@{B}Auto-Iconify@{UB} keeps the Emulation Control Window from opening.
Instead, an icon is placed on Workbench.  To open the Emulation Control
Window, just double-click the icon.

@{B}Start Delay@{UB} will delay the booting of the Macintosh system
software for approximately 4 seconds.  This gives you extra time to press
(and HOLD) either SHIFT key to disable the Macintosh System Extensions.
On a very fast Amiga, there generally not enough time without this delay
enabled.

The @{B}Foreground Priority@{UB} and @{B}Background Priority@{UB} slider gadgets
allow you to set the priority you wish the Mac to run at while it is the
active screen or when it is inactive, respectively.  FUSION does not
busy loop under most conditions, so these priorities are not as critical
as they used to be.  If you have a lower priority task that seems to be
having trouble running, try lowering the priorities.
@ENDNODE AdvancedOpt
@NODE ConfigOpt "Load or Save Configuration"

                       @{B}Configuration Option@{UB}

Click on @{B}Save Configuration@{UB} to get a requester for the name to save the
configuration under.  The name it comes up with by default should be used if
you wish to have the configuration load automatically the next time you run
the emulation.  You may save the configuration under a different name, but
you will have to load it using Load Configuration, or run FUSION from a CLI
with the -c switch.  See @{"Emulation Setup Window" link Setup}

Click on @{B}Load Configuration@{UB}, or press L to get a requester for the name
of the configuration file to load.  This allows you to have different
configurations saved under different names.

Clicking on @{B}Delete PRAM@{UB} will display a requestor that allows you to
select the PRAMxxx.config file to be deleted.  The 'xxx' will be either
256, 512, or 1mb, depending on the size of the MAC ROM image you are using.
@ENDNODE ConfigOpt
@NODE Control "Emulation Control Window"

        Once the emulation is running, a small window or an icon is placed
on Workbench.  It allows the user to control various aspects of FUSION.
The icon expands to the Emulation Control Window when it is double clicked.
The buttons on the Emulation Control Window may be clicked with the mouse,
or the underlined character may be pressed while the window is active.

        The controls are:

	@{"ICP Control   " link ICPCtl}		@{"Video Control" link VideoCtl}
	@{"Device Control" link DeviceCtl}		@{"CPU Control  " link CPUCtl}
	@{"POWER OFF     " link PowerCtl}		@{"Mac to Front " link FrontCtl}

        Clicking on the close gadget iconifies the Emulation Control Window.
While using the Emulation Control Window, pressing the Escape key does the
same thing as clicking the close gadget.

The window position of ALL the windows in the 'Control' group are remembered
each time you move a window.  These positions can be permanently saved after
the emulation is shut down by saving the config file.
@ENDNODE Control
@NODE ICPCtl "InterCommunications Port Control"

                 @{B}InterCommunications Port Control@{UB}

The control window contains a listview of currently selected volumes and
three gadgets:  @{B}Add Entry@{UB}, @{B}Remove Entry@{UB}, and @{B}Information@{UB}.

Select a volume in the listview and click on @{B}Remove Entry@{UB},or press R to
dismount (if mounted) and remove the entry from the listview.  Click on
@{B}Information@{UB}, or press I for information about the volume.  The
information includes the Mac Volume Name, the Amiga Volume name, whether
it is mounted, the number of open files, and the number of locks.  If
the open count or the lock count are not zero, you cannot dismount the
volume.

Click on the @{B}Add Entry@{UB} button, or press A to get a requester with all
the current Mac volumes that are not already in the list.  You must hit
RETURN to officially Add the entry.  If you click on a name and then the
close gadget, it aborts the operation.  Once you have selected a name,
hit RETURN to mount the volume, or change the name in the string gadget
and hit RETURN to mount in under a name different than the one the Mac
is using.  This is useful if you have a Mac volume with the same name
as one of your Amiga Volumes.

The listview shows the currently selected volumes; their state is denoted by
an asterisk: the asterisk shows the volume has been mounted under AmigaDOS.
A volume without an asterisk is waiting for the volume to be mounted on the
Mac side.  A removable media volume may be mounted using the ICP; when it
is ejected on the Mac side, it is dismounted on the Amiga side automatically;
the asterisk goes away showing the volume is no longer mounted.

If you then insert a new volume with the same name in the removable media
drive, it will automatically remount on the Amiga side.  If you insert a
volume with a different name, you will have to select it to mount it on the
Amiga.  Any number of volumes may be waiting in the list, but only the first
16 are saved to the configuration file when you save the configuration after
shutting down the emulation.

Once a volume has been mounted, you can access it from the Amiga side just
like you would any other AmigaDOS volume.  

There are a few differences in the way the Mac OS handles files.  You can
not delete an entire directory of files.  You must first delete all of the
files inside of the folder before the folder itself can be deleted.

Please note that DirectoryOpus (which we highly recommend) does not support
directory or file names longer than 30 characters.  The Mac OS supports
directory and file names up to 31 characters.  This is a restriction of
Directory Opus v4.x and earlier.  DirectoryOpus 5.x's Workbench replacement
does NOT show Volumes that do not have an associated device (handlers only),
so an icon will not appear on the Workbench replacement for a mounted Mac
volume.  You can however, go to the device list and still open the device
and use it normally.

Mac files have two sections called @{B}forks@{UB}.  The @{B}File Translation@{UB} cycle
gadget allows you to select the way DOS deals with these forks:

	@{B}Intelligent@{UB} - If the file has only a data fork, only the data
fork is read from the Amiga side.  If the file has a resource fork, the
file is read from the Amiga side as MacBinary format.  This is a special
format where a header is read first, then the data fork (if there is one),
then the resource fork (if there is one).  If a file is written to the
Mac from the Amiga, it is examined to see if it is a MacBinary file; if
it is, it is written to the Mac as a normal Mac file.  If it is not a
MacBinary file, it is written as a data fork only file, and the file type
and creator are set from the gadgets in the control window.

	@{B}MacBinary@{UB} - The file is read from the Amiga side as MacBinary
format under all conditions.  If a file is written to the Mac from the
Amiga, it is examined to see if it is a MacBinary file; if it is, it is
written to the Mac as a normal Mac file.  If it is not a MacBinary file,
it is written as a data fork only file, and the file type and creator
are set from the gadgets in the control window.

	@{B}Resource Fork@{UB} - Only the file's resource fork is read or written
by the Amiga.  New files (Amiga to Mac) use the file type and creator in the
gadgets in the control window.

	@{B}Data Fork@{UB} - Only the file's data fork is read or written by the
Amiga.  New files (Amiga to Mac) use the file type and creator in the
gadgets in the control window.

The Data Fork mode is the mode most users should use for copying Amiga
or PC files (text/graphics) to or from the Mac.  If you are copying a
MacBinary file (e.g., a demo archive downloaded from a Mac BBS), use
Intelligent or MacBinary.

The file @{B}Type@{UB} and @{B}Creator@{UB} string gadgets hold the current file type
and creator to use when copying a file to the Mac.  These values are over-
ridden by the file type and creator in the header of a MacBinary format
file in Intelligent or MacBinary mode.

New for v3.0 is the ability to select the FILE TYPE and CREATOR from a
Database.  Click on @{B}Database@{UB}, or press D to go the Database
editor.  You will see a list of File Descriptions in the window.  When you
click on any entry, the name will appear in the File Description box and
the File Type and Creator for this entry will be shown in the appropriate
boxes.  Once an entry has been selected, you can edit the boxes to change
the information about that entry.  You can also exit back to the main
ICP window, and the last selected entry will then be used as the current
File Type and Creator for file transfers.

Clicking on @{B}Add@{UB} will add a new entry to the Database, and allow
you to edit the entry.  Clicking on @{B}Copy@{UB} will duplicate the
currently selected entry, and allow you to edit the entry.  Clicking on
@{B}Remove@{UB} will delete the currently selected entry from the Database.
Clicking on @{B}Sort@{UB} will do an alphabetical sort on the Database.
Clicking on @{B}Clear@{UB} will clear all entries in the Database, and
add 'Default Text' automatically.  Clicking on @{B}Import@{UB} will allow
you to merge another Database with the current one.  The Import works by
checking each entry in the imported Database against the current Database.
All identical File Type and Creator entries are ignored, and only those
that do not exist in the current Database are added.  Clicking on @{B}Load@{UB}
will allow you to load a new Database, which will take the place of the
current Database.  Clicking on @{B}Save@{UB} will allow you to save the
current Database.

When a Database is loaded (FUSION:FUSION.db is the default path/name), there
is enough space to manually enter 100 entries.  If you Clear the Database,
there is also enough space to manually enter 100 entries.  If you Import
another Database larger than 100 entries, only the first valid 100 entries
will be imported.  If this happens, you would need to then save the current
Database, Load it again (anytime you Load a Database, enough space
for 100 additional entries is created), and Import the Database again.  You
would have to repeat this process as many times as necessary to Import all
of the new Database file.  It is unlikely that anyone will have more than
100 entries to add at one time, so this method was used to conserve memory.
@ENDNODE ICPCtrl
@NODE VideoCtl "Video Control"

                           @{B}Video Controls@{UB}

This control window allows the user to set two video options on the fly.
Select a video driver in the listview, then you may change:

	@{B}QDXL Support@{UB} - Some Mac programs do not draw properly with Quick-
Draw Acceleration turned on.  You may turn it on or off here.  Only direct
drivers support acceleration.

	@{B}Refresh Rate@{UB} - You may changed the rate at which the display is
updated.  Lower frame rates allow the emulation to run faster, while
higher frame rates give smoother video.  Only refreshed drivers have
an adjustable Refresh Rate.
@ENDNODE VideoCtl
@NODE DeviceCtl "Device Remount Control"

                          @{B}Device Control@{UB}

This control window allows you to remount ALL drives which have been
thrown in the thrash by the user on the Mac side.  This eliminates
having to reboot the Mac to get back back non-removable drives.

Just click on @{B}Remount Ejected@{UB}, or press R.
@ENDNODE DeviceCtl
@NODE CPUCtl "CPU Cache Control"

                            @{B}CPU Control@{UB}

This control window allows you to turn on or off the data or instruction
caches.  Click the appropriate Check Box or use the keyboard to toggle the
state of each cache.  Some @{I}really@{UI} old Mac programs will not work
with some or all of the caches turned on; if you are having trouble running
an old program (especially on an 040/060), try turning off the data cache
first, then try both the data and instruction caches off.  For 060 users,
try to keep the SuperScalar, Branch Cache, Store/Load Bypass, & Store Buffer
OFF as much as possible since no programmer in the Macintosh market ever
had to program around 060 problems.

The most significant reduction in speed for the emulation comes from having
the Branch Cache turned off.  There are quite a few known applications
(such as Microsoft Word) that will not run with the Branch Cache on.  We
think that the problem has to do with the 060 being too fast for most
application's delay loops.
@ENDNODE CPUCtl
@NODE PowerCtl "Power-Off Control"

                        @{B}@{U}Emergency@{UU} Power Off@{UB}

This control window allows you to @{I}force@{UI} the emulation to quit.  Do not
do this lightly as you will lose all information on the Mac side.  Try
the Forced-Quit first (Alt-Amiga-Esc) if an application hangs when run.
@ENDNODE PowerCtl
@NODE FrontCtl "Mac to Front"

                           @{B}Mac to Front@{UB}

Brings the Mac screen that the Mac mouse is on to the front and activates
it.  A quick way back to the emulation when you have a lot of screens open.
@ENDNODE FrontCtl
@NODE Concerns "Abilities & Limitations"

FUSION is almost a @{I}port@{UI} of the MacOS to the Amiga.  As such, its
capabilities are unrivaled.  That does not mean that it is 100% compatible
(even real Macs aren't, depending on the Mac and the software in question).

The Mac System Software must be installed using the generic Installation
Package that is sold through Mac retailers.  Software shipped with a Mac
is specific to that Mac only!  E.G., I (Joe) own a PowerMac (among all the
dozen or so computers I own); the CD-ROM that came with it will not work
on ANY other Mac I have tried it on.  It just has the resources for itself.
Once you have the generic System Software, do NOT do an Easy install, as
that will only install the resources needed by the Mac indicated by the
machine ID.  As we allow the machine ID to be set by the user, you can
indicate a Mac that does not have certain resources FUSION needs.  A Custom
Installation must be performed; you must make sure that you select
@{B}System for Any Macintosh@{UB} or you may wind up missing some resources.
You might get away with using disks shipped with a Mac or doing an Easy
Install, but probably not, and certainly you will see trouble at some
point.  I talked to one user who did an Easy Install and had trouble with
some programs, but not others; after re-installing for any Mac, these
problems went away.  You are forewarned.

Some programs make improper assumptions about the layout of memory; we
have made patches for some of those that you can find on various nets.
Some are patched as they load by FUSION.  Others simply cannot be fixed.
Fortunately, these types of programs are rare.

Some programs claim to be 32bit clean, but still have some code in them
that prevents them from actually running if they load above a certain
address.  On a real Mac, this will not be seen unless the Mac has more
than 16MBytes RAM.  FUSION must use RAM for the Mac that is above the
point that these "dirty" programs will accept on most Amigas.  Two things
have been done about this: we have made patches for some programs that
can be found on the net, and we have implemented a Pseudo-24bit mode.
The pseudo-24bit mode uses the MMU to map memory down below the point
that causes trouble with these programs.  If you have problems with some
programs, try pseudo-24bit mode.  Two programs we know must be run in this
mode are Drol and ShadowWraith.  Note: the program must at least "claim"
to be 32bit clean for it to work in pseudo-24bit mode; this mode will
@{B}NOT@{UB} run programs requiring 24bit addressing mode.  FUSION does
not support true 24bit addressing and neither does Apple since switching
to PPC.

Some programs poke the hardware directly.  FUSION has been designed to
handle a lot of this. Having an EMPLANT card enhances this capability.
However, some direct poking cannot be handled; any program that uses
fixed addresses for the hardware will have problems; the global variables
must be used to fetch the hardware addresses.  Poking the floppy control-
ler direct will not work, but won't crash (Apple DiskCopy is an example of
this).  Audio can be poked into the ASC as long as it follows the old
compatibility guideline for direct audio (PacMan is an example of this).
@ENDNODE Concerns
@NODE ICP "ICP Information"
In the FUSION:ICP directory, you will find some useful programs that allow
you to launch Macintosh applications from your Workbench or CLI, and do
other functions (such as remotely turning off the Macintosh, thus quitting
the emulation).  The source code to these applications is available on
our web site (http://www.ctaz.com/~msdei).

                           @{B}LaunchApp@{UB}

The program LaunchApp is used to start up a Macintosh program.  You can use
LaunchApp through the CLI:

LaunchApp Work:SimpleText

This will launch the program 'SimpleText' (a Macintosh text editor included
with all Macs) providing that it is located on the Mac partition labeled as
'Work'.  The Macintosh uses different path conventions from the Amiga.
Instead of using the forward slash '/' between directory paths, Apple uses
the semicolon ':' always.  For example:

LaunchApp Work:graphics:utilities:PhotoShop2.51:PhotoShop2.5.1

In many cases, Macintosh names will have special characters.  To re-create
these characters, you will need to figure out what key combinations are
required.  Here are a few of the common ones:

Bullet (small solid circle) = ALT-SHIFT-Y      (Ą)
TradeMark Symbol (TM)       = ALT-V            (Ş)
Copyright Symbol (C)        = ALT-E            (©)
Registered Symbol (R)       = ALT-R            (®)
Mac folder symbol (f)       = ALT-K, SHIFT-A   (Ä)

You can also use LaunchApp through Workbench.  You must create an icon
for each application you want to launch.  In the tooltype, you must set
the default tool to FUSION:ICP/LaunchApp.  You must set the TOOLTYPE to
be APPL=xxxx, where 'xxxx' is the full path to the Macintosh application
in the format described above (ie APPL=Work:SimpleText).  There is a
sample icon included for SimpleText, take a look at it.

                           @{B}ShutDownPower@{UB}

The ShutDownPower program is just a program that calls the Macintosh
shutdown routine.  Note, this is not the same as using the ShutDown function
from the Mac's pull-down menu.  No application will be told to close its
files, so data will be lost.  This is the same as using the POWEROFF option
in the ICP Control Window.
@ENDNODE ICP
@NODE Trouble "Trouble Shooting"

                         @{B}Trouble Shooting@{UB}

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to allocate any 32 bit memory!'.

Select configure option Memory and decrease the amount of memory
being selected.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'ROM image file not found!'.

Select configure option ROM Image and make sure a ROM Image is selected.
It is also possible you do not have FUSION: assigned to the FUSION drawer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Invalid ROM - ID word incorrect!'.

Select configure option ROM Image and make sure the ROM Type is Mac II/
x/cx, Mac IIsi/ci/lc, or Mac Quadra/Performa.  Any other type ROM cannot
be used with FUSION MAC68K.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Invalid ROM image checksum!'.

In some cases, having the ROMUtil save directly to a floppy causes a
bad file to be saved; save to the harddrive and drag the file to the
floppy.  On the Amiga side, make sure CrossPC is not set for translating
Carriage Returns to Line Feeds or vice versa as this will corrupt the
ROM image when copied to the ROM_Images drawer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Video driver file not found!'.

Select configure option Video and make sure a video driver is selected.
It is also possible you do not have FUSION: assigned to the FUSION drawer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to start video process!'.

If you are using a video card, make sure all the necessary software for
the card is present and operating.  Make sure you have available at
least a 640x480 256 color mode.  If you are not using a video card,
make sure you have the needed monitor file in the DEVS:Monitors drawer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to start emulation process!'.

Make sure you are not using any multitasking enhancement programs on the
Amiga.  Reboot the Amiga and try again.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Low memory not reserved!'.

Make sure that RsrvCold or RsrvWarm is being run in the startup-sequence.
This should have been added by the Installer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'No SYSTEM memory selected!'.

Select configure option Memory and make sure you have a memory block
selected and memory allocated for the System with the slider.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'ROM image not selected!'.

Select configure option ROM Image and make sure a ROM Image is selected.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to open AmigaDOS device!'.

Select configure option Devices; if you have a hardfile selected, make
sure mshf.device is in your DEVS: drawer.  If you selected a device,
make sure it is a harddrive, partition, or some kind of disk drive
like CatWeasel; no other type devices can be selected.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'This software requires a 68020+ CPU'.

You are running on an Amiga with a 68000 or 68010.  You must upgrade
the CPU to at least an 68020.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'No video driver(s) selected!'.

Select configure option Video and make sure a video driver is selected.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'External I/O driver is REQUIRED!'.

Select configure option Peripherals, click on ADB and choose a software
driver.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to setup external I/O driver!'.

You have something interfering with commodities; reboot and try again.
If it still has a problem, remove a commodities programs you may be
running, reboot and try again.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to initialize the video hardware!'.

You either have selected a video card driver that does not have at least
a 640x480 256 color mode, or you didn't leave enough memory free for the
video card driver to allocate for its own use.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to initialize the audio hardware!'.

You have selected AHI and have a problem with the AHI software, or you
need to reboot the Amiga.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message '1792K+ System Size REQUIRED!'.

Select configure option Memory and make sure to select (with the slider)
at least 1792KBytes of memory.  Actually, for System 7.5.x or later,
you should select at least 4096KBytes.  If you cannot select enough
memory, try another memory block.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to open serial device driver!'.

Select configure option Ports; if you have set one of the ports to
serial, make sure the device name has been entered correctly (device
names are case sensitive!) and that unit number is correct.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to open parallel device driver!'.

Select configure option Ports; if you have set one of the ports to
parallel, make sure the device name has been entered correctly (device
names are case sensitive!) and that unit number is correct.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to open 'multi-os.device'!'.

Make sure multi-os.device is in the DEVS: drawer.  Reinstall FUSION.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to open 'clipboard.device'!'.

Make sure clipboard.device is in the DEVS: drawer.  Copy it from your
original Workbench disks if not.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Please update 'clipboard.device'.'.

Some other Amiga program installed an old copy of clipboard.device into
the DEVS: drawer. Recopy clipboard.device from your original Workbench
disk.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Unable to open 'amia.device'!'.

You have selected the AMIA as one of your floppies, but amia.device is
not in the DEVS: drawer.  Reinstall FUSION.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error message 'Improper device driver for CD-ROM setup!'.

Select configure option Peripherals, click on CD-ROM, make sure the
device name has been entered correctly (device names are case sensitive!)
and that the unit number is correct.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I get the error 'Can't initialize Amiga timer hardware!'.

You are running some other programs on the Amiga using the timers.  Try
quitting some of these other programs and try again.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I start the emulator, get a blank screen, and then the Amiga hangs or
gurus.

The ROM image you have selected may not be compatible.  Reread all the
sections concerning the ROM image.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I start the emulator, get a gray screen and a tone, then a floppy with
a question mark appears.

This is the Mac boot screen; insert a bootable Mac floppy disk.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I inserted a disk in the drive, but it ignores it.

Make sure you have the correct drive selected for the Mac.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I inserted a disk in the drive, but it showed an X.

The disk is either not bootable, or in a format the floppy drive cannot
handle.  Remember that high-density disks must be read in a high-density
drive.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I inserted a disk and got the 'Happy Mac'; then part of the way through
booting, I got a Dialog saying that the disk wasn't suitable for this
Mac.

You are trying to use System Software that was shipped with a real Mac.
It will not work on FUSION.  Reread the abilities and limitations.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I inserted a disk and got the 'Happy Mac'; then part of the way through
booting, I got a bomb box.

You are trying to boot System 7.0 or 7.0.1.  You must use 7.1 or newer.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I booted the Install 1 disk, but it doesn't find the harddrive I selected.

You must boot the Disk Tools disk the first time; the Install disk does
not have the resources needed to format the harddrive.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I installed the System Software, but it doesn't boot all the way on
restart afterwards.

You probably did an Easy Install.  Reinstall, making sure to install
System for Any Macintosh.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I have been running ok for awhile, but lately, I have been having problems
running applications that ran fine before.

It's time to reinstall!  Mac System Software works by corrupting itself;
eventually, you have to reinstall.  System 7.5.3 and newer are not as
bad as earlier systems, and System 7.1.x usually needs to be reinstalled
once a month.  When you reinstall the System, we recommend you also
delete the PRAMxxx.Config file as well.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I want to rebuild the desktop; how do I do it?

After the 'Welcome to Macintosh', hold Alt and Amiga (either pair, it
doesn't matter which) until a dialog appears asking if you really want
to rebuild the desktop.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I booted the emulation and everything is black and white.

Go into the Mac control panels and run Monitors; switch into color mode
and select the number of colors you want.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I just switched from Amiga to AHI audio, and now I get no sound.

Go into the Mac control panels and run Sound; use the pop-up menu to
select Output Devices. this forces the Mac to re-do the audio prefs and
switch to the new audio output device.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I'm using a direct Cybergraphics or Picasso96 driver on a card that
support direct thousands or millions of colors, but only get 256 colors.

Make sure that the proper mode is available.  Also, you will only get
256 colors with those drivers if you are not using the MMU.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I have Workbench on my video card and use a direct driver; when I flip
screens, the Mac trashes my Workbench.

Flip screens with suspension.  To do this, hold the Left Shift key while
flipping screens.  This will halt the Mac, even in the middle of a drive
access or playing a QuickTime movie!  The Mac will resume execution if
you reactivate its display or try to use a volume mounted through ICP.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I am running the Mac in a window on Workbench and I can't get back to
Workbench!

Remember, click both right and left mouse buttons at the same time, or
click the middle button of a three button mouse.  Attempting to flip
screens with suspension will also deactivate the window (as well as the
Mac!).

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I am running the Mac in a window on Workbench and I only get 16 and 256
colors.

You must have Workbench on a Cybergraphics or Picasso96 card in 15, 16,
24, or 32bit depth.  At that point, you will be able to do 16, 256, and
millions of colors (thousands is not available because Cybergraphics and
Picasso96 don't support it with WritePixelArray()).

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I am running the Mac in a window on Workbench and am only using 256
colors.  How do I make it run faster?

Make sure Workbench is set to a depth of 256 colors.  Try lowering
the refresh rate.  Also, turn off the Mac Menu Bar Clock.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

When running some programs, I get a MAC bomb box with an error 90.
What is wrong?

Error 90 is an FPU error.  This error occurs when an application
attempts to use the FPU directly, and one does not exist.  You must
install an FPU in order to correct this problem.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I am trying to run the Duke Nukem 3D demo on a stock CD32/SX with 8MBytes
of RAM but can't quite get enough memory.

:^} Seriously, I did this on mine.

Remove everything possible from the Workbench (no commodities or startups
or DOSDrivers), don't add any buffers to anything, boot the CD32,
and do the command 'Avail Flush' to force everything out of memory.
Run NoFastMem, then run FUSION.  Select only the CD32_DQDRfresh driver,
select a 256K ROM image, don't select a CD-ROM, don't select any devices
other than the one with the System and Duke Nukem 3D.  Don't select AHI
audio, just Amiga audio.  You should now be able to select 7.5MBytes
of RAM (it will find the node even though you ran NoFastMem because of
the way we look at Amiga Memory).  If you boot with extensions off, you
should just have enough to run Duke Nukem 3D.  You'll have to run in low
resolution with a small screen size, and you'll only get 2 to 3 frames
per second, but it works!

---------------------------------------------------------------------

I'm trying to boot with extensions off, how do I do it?

You have to hold the shift key down while booting (either one).  The
tricky part is that if you push the key before the Amiga screen for the
Mac opens, the key is not recognized; however, if you wait too long,
you'll get 'Welcome to Macintosh' and it's too late.  you have to press
the shift key right between those two events (right about the time the
'Happy Mac' appears).
@ENDNODE Trouble
@NODE History "Emulation Version Information"

**************************************************************************

Changes to V2.0 (09/01/97)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
* Added SCSI-direct support.  Please note that any Macintosh application
  that attempts to poke at the SCSI hardware port directly will crash.
  You should now be able to use any Amiga SCSI controller to directly
  control any SCSI device (ie. DATs, scanners, hard drives, CD-ROM drives,
  digital cameras, etc.)  Here is a list of problem encoutered:

  Retrospect 2.0i (and earlier) is not 32 bit clean.  You will need to run
  this program in Psuedo 24 mode or it will not properly store/restore
  any data.

  SilverLining 5.5 (and earlier) hangs when you attempt to do the TIME
  SCSI LOOP test.  This is because SilverLining's custom routines poke
  at the SCSI hardware directly (which does not exist).

  Software that calls SCSI-direct functions from inside of an interrupt will
  not work.  It is not possible to call Amiga SCSI-direct commands from
  inside of an interrupt.  MAC programs (a few CD-ROM drivers) that do this
  will never get a SCSI status back, but at least they will not crash the
  machine.

* Corrected OS8.0 problems with 060s.  Please note that Apple decided to
  not allow 060s to work under OS8.0, and thus the only way to make
  it work is by turning off the SuperScalar.  Please do not turn on the
  SuperScaler after OS8.0 has booted... we turn it off, and leave it off
  until the emulation is shut down.  Yes, your system will run slower..
  but there is nothing that can be done about this problem... Apple wants
  you to buy a PowerPC machine!

* Corrected various ROM incompatibilty problems.

* Added ability to turn off or select one of the 5 internal Macintosh
  startup sounds.

* Changed Virtual Base setup.  Please see the documentation concerning
  the changes.

* Added memory test option.  This is a sure fire way to determine if your
  MMU is working properly with your memory nodes and to see if you have
  RAM refresh problems.

* MMU usage is now system friendly if possible, merging into existing
  tables.  This should allow other Amiga applications (run before FUSION)
  to use the MMU (ie. GigaMem).  The new method does not consume additional
  memory, which was previously required for the MMU table space.

* ALL of the video drivers are new, and not compatible with previous
  versions of FUSION.

* Changed the Cybergraphics drivers to allow for v2.x or 3.x of the
  Cybergraphics software.  Please note: some of the QuickDraw acceleration
  routines WILL fail under v2.x, please upgrade... it's free.
  (http://www.best.com/~vgr)

* Fixed a device entry limitation.  Amiga systems with more than 13
  mounted devices would not show ALL of the devices (after the first
  13 were shown, the rest were ignored).

* Corrected device closing problem, sometimes resulting in a system crash
  when shutting down the emulation.

* Added new option in the DEVICE OPTIONS sub-menu of the DEVICES menu.  Now
  along with FORCED WRITE PROTECT, DMA RESTRICTIONS, and REMOVABLE MEDIA
  is the option SKIP VALIDATION.  Selecting gadget (making the check in
  the box visable) will not allow the MAC to immediately validate a partition.
  There is a strange problem with OS8.0 with validation, and we believe it
  is a bug in the intial release of OS8.0 (no other OS has this problem).
  The problem is this: shutdown improperly (ie crash or do an emergency
  power-off) and the partition will not boot properly.  The next time you
  attempt to boot, the 'smiley MAC' will appear, the MAC will reset, and
  this sequence is repeated forever.  Skipping the validation of the drive
  at boot time fixes this problem.  Note: validation still does occur, just
  not at boot time.


**************************************************************************

Changes to V1.1 (07/27/97)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
* Fixed AMAX II+/IV hardware timing characteristics.  We forgot that the
  EMPLANT hardware runs about 20% faster than a real MAC.  The AMAX II+/IV
  hardware runs at the normal MAC speed.

* Fixed incompatibility problem with certain Motorola instructions that
  have bugs.

* Added memory dispatch routines when virtual memory is not in place.

* Fixed a couple of mistakes in the interface, most notibly the START
  EMULATOR keyboard event (pressing 'S' to start the emulation).  Some
  of the sub-menus (FLOPPY, PORTS, ROM, & SOUND) did not look at the
  keyboard at all.

* Fixed a problem with virtual memory on the Performa 475 ROMs.

* Re-wrote memory selection slider code to avoid bug in OS3.0's GadTools.

* Re-wrote memory speed/type code to be 100% accurate when reporting
  memory speed rating (which is in megabytes per second) and the memory
  type (16 bit or 32 bit).

* Changed the display for memory type from '32bit' to FAST32, '16 bit'
  to 'FAST16', and CHIP to be either 'CHIP32' or 'CHIP16' depending on
  the memory type.

* Enhanced QuickDraw acceleration routines for inverted data.

* Corrected CD-ROM recognition with bootable CD-ROMs and CD-ROMs that have
  multiple partition maps.

* Added the ability to save the position of every window that is part of
  the Control Window group.  This includes the Main Control Window,
  ICPControl Window, Device Window, Video Driver Window, Power Off Window,
  CPU Cache Window, etc.  You can move these windows where you like, and
  once you shutdown the emulation, saving the config file will also save
  the position of all windows.  The next you boot, the windows will be
  where you left them last.

* Added the ability to change the boot priority of the built-in CD-ROM
  drive support.  You can now select between FIRST and LAST as the boot
  priorities.  Selecting FIRST will put the CD-ROM before any other
  AmigaDOS (or SCSI via EMPLANT's SCSI port) device.  If the CD-ROM disc
  is bootable (like OS8.0 is), it will boot from it.  Selecting LAST
  puts the CD-ROM last in the list of bootable devices.

* Updated mscd.device to support new CD-ROM changes.


**************************************************************************

Changes to V1.0 (07/01/97)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
First release ... no changes.


@ENDNODE History
@NODE Glossary "Glossary of Terms"

                              @{B}Glossary@{UB}

                                  @{B}A@{UB}

	@{B}active window@{UB}:  This is the window with which the user interacts.
Its title bar is highlighted--by color on the Amiga, by lines on the Mac.

	@{B}ASC@{UB}:  Apple Sound Chip.  Hardware that Apple computers use for
producing audio.  2 Channel stereo/mono sound.

	@{B}ADB@{UB}:  Apple Desktop Bus.  Hardware that Apple computers use for
user-input devices--such as the keyboard, the mouse, and graphic tablets.

	@{B}addressing@{UB}:  24- or 32-bit.  This is a feature of memory on the Mac
which allows it to operate more efficiently and use larger amounts of memory
(in 32-bit mode).

	@{B}alert@{UB}:  A warning which the system gives.  It appears in a box and
usually allows the user to choose between one of two actions.

	@{B}AMIA@{UB}:  Amiga Macintosh Interface Adapter.  An adapter which allows
the user to read and write Mac 800K (low density) format disks.

	@{B}AppleTalk@{UB}:  An Apple computer network device--allowing various
computers to interact.

	@{B}application@{UB}:  A program that works with one specific purpose, such
as record keeping or graphics.

	@{B}assignment@{UB}:  A name that programs can use instead of needing to
search for a directory.  For example:  "FONTS:" instead of "DH3:Fonts/"

                                  @{B}B@{UB}

	@{B}backup@{UB}:  A copy of files.  If files are lost or get corrupted, the
backup can replace them.

	@{B}baud@{UB}:  Speed at which communication devices operate.  Derived from
the term "bits per second."

	@{B}bit@{UB}:  A binary digit (i.e., 0 or 1).

	@{B}blit@{UB}: A term derived from bit block transfer.  This refers to the
movement of data as a block of bits.  The data may be changed as it is moved.

	@{B}blitter@{UB}: Hardware used to do blits.  Often used to speed up video
operations like scrolling.

	@{B}boot@{UB}:  Start the system by reading initial information off a storage
device, such as a floppy disk or hard drive.

	@{B}bridgeboard@{UB}:  An expansion board that emulates a PC with hardware.

	@{B}buffer@{UB}:  Memory used for storing information so that the program can
continue while the system waits for whatever uses the information.  A device
buffer, for example, allows the emulation to continue working while the
device handler waits for the device to transfer the information.

	@{B}bug@{UB}:  A term which refers to a small problem--usually a mistake or
an omission.

	@{B}bus@{UB}:  Circuitry that connects one part of the computer to another.

	@{B}"busy" drive@{UB}:  State in which a drive is "locked" and cannot be
accessed by programs which do not hold the lock.  The Mac emulation will
lock the floppy drives in this state if you select Mac control of the floppy
drives.

	@{B}busy loop@{UB}:  A programming technique that causes the CPU to be busy
doing nothing until a set duration has passed.

	@{B}byte@{UB}:  One unit of information ranging from -128 to 127, consisting
of eight bits.  Often used in multiples to form larger values or strings of
information.  For example, a long word consists of four bytes and has a
combined range of -2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647.

	For ease, larger units are referred to by their approximate size:

kilobyte (K):  1,024 bytes
megabyte (M):  1,024 x 1,024 bytes
gigabyte (G):  1,024 x 1,024 x 1,024 bytes

                                  @{B}C@{UB}

	@{B}cache@{UB}:  Memory that is specifically designated for buffering
purposes. @{I}See buffer.@{UI}

	@{B}checksum@{UB}:  A value which represents the "sum" of a file's entire
data.  This is used to verify that the file has not been corrupted.

	@{B}chip@{UB}:  Integrated circuit.  A small electronic circuit designed to
produce specific data, or to convert data into a usable form.

	@{B}chunk@{UB}:  A set of data whose parts reside next to each other,
allowing programs to assume simple (fast) routines for referring to it.
@{I}See fragment.@{UI}

	@{B}clipboard@{UB}:  Memory that is used for holding information which the
user cuts, copies, or pastes.

	@{B}code@{UB}:  General term for a program--as opposed to data or
information.  This term also refers to the way a device communicates with a
program.

	@{B}compatibility@{UB}:  The degree to which the emulation meets a program's
expectations.  In most ways, the Mac emulator succeeds.

	@{B}compression@{UB}:  A method for storing redundant or simple data in a
complex fashion, allowing it to be made smaller.  @{I}See decompression.@{UI}

	@{B}configuration@{UB}:  The settings that tell the program how to prepare
itself for your use.

	@{B}controller@{UB}:  A circuit which decides how a device is used.  For
example, a hard drive controller decides how to store and retrieve its data.

	@{B}CopyBack@{UB}:  A processor mode which takes advantage of specially
structured programs, allowing them to run a lot faster than normal.

	@{B}CPU@{UB}:  Central Processing Unit.  The main integrated circuit that
programs use to control the computer.

	@{B}crash@{UB}:  This is when the system or a device has a very serious
problem and often needs to be restarted or repaired in order to fix the
problem.  @{I}See boot.@{UI}

                                  @{B}D@{UB}

	@{B}decompression@{UB}:  Method for reproducing information from very
complex data.  @{I}See compression.@{UI}

	@{B}default@{UB}:  The settings a program uses unless it is told to do
otherwise.  @{I}See configuration.@{UI}

	@{B}desktop@{UB}:  The Mac equivalent of Workbench--the environment on which
the user opens windows and shows program icons.  Unlike Workbench, however,
desktop is a reference to an aspect of Finder (Mac's DOS).  @{I}See Finder.@{UI}

	@{B}disk@{UB}:  A special surface contained in a plastic shell on which
information can be recorded magnetically.  Optical disks use lasers to read
and write optical information.

	@{B}DMA@{UB}:  Direct Memory Access.  A design that allows devices or special
co-processors to read or write into memory without disturbing other
processors (i.e., the CPU).

	@{B}DOS@{UB}:  Disk Operating System.  A system program which includes a file
system and a method of interpreting and executing particular files.  @{I}See
file system.@{UI}

	@{B}DOSDriver@{UB}:  Device driver that adds more control, giving DOS more
ways to store or retrieve files.

	@{B}double-click@{UB}:  Quickly pressing the (left) mouse button twice.

	@{B}drag@{UB}:  Holding down the mouse button while moving the mouse.

	@{B}drawer@{UB}:  A subdivision of a file storage area--a DOS sub-directory.
Drawers allow you to organize data better, particularly on large storage
devices like hard drives.  @{I}See folder.@{UI}

	@{B}drive@{UB}:  A device that stores and retrieves information from disks.

	@{B}driver@{UB}:  A system program that directs the control of data to and
from a specific part of the computer or a particular device.

	@{B}dump@{UB}:  Term for storing binary data directly to a file, usually from
a chunk of data.  @{I}See chunk.@{UI}

                                  @{B}E@{UB}

	@{B}eject@{UB}:  Remove a disk from the drive (with the eject button).

	@{B}EMPLANT@{UB}:  Electronic Micro-Processor Level Amiga Native Task.
Special hardware designed to facilitate various emulations.

	@{B}emulation@{UB}:  A system that translates the functions of a different
computer into ones the user's computer understands, letting programs
intended for the other computer to operate on the user's.

	@{B}expansion@{UB}:  Hardware designed to add memory and/or functionality
to your computer.

	@{B}extension@{UB}:  Mac equivalent of a driver.  This adds to the
capabilities of the system and the desktop.  Also called INIT.

                                  @{B}F@{UB}

	@{B}file system@{UB}:  Software that controls how data is organized, passing
the information along to the user or driver; often a substitute for or a
part of DOS.  @{I}See DOS.@{UI}

	@{B}Finder@{UB}:  Mac system software that controls files and the desktop.

	@{B}floppy@{UB}:  Disk created with a flexible plastic.  @{I}See disk.@{UI}

	@{B}folder@{UB}:  Mac equivalent of a drawer.  A sub-directory in which the
user can place files and organize data.  @{I}See drawer.@{UI}

	@{B}format@{UB}:  The way sectors are arranged on a disk in preparation for
use by a Disk operating system.  @{I}See DOS.@{UI}

	@{B}FPS@{UB}:  Frames per second.  @{I}See refresh.@{UI}

	@{B}fragment@{UB}:  A group of data which represents part of a set.  To
fragment means to cause data to be scattered over a storage region.  To
defragment means to arrange the data so that all the parts follow each other
sequentially.  @{I}See chunk.@{UI}

                                  @{B}G@{UB}

	@{B}gadget@{UB}:  An image that represents a specific function of a program.
Often used to answer a question that the program asks.

	@{B}gigabyte@{UB}:  1,024 megabytes.  Often abbreviated as "gig."

                                  @{B}H@{UB}

	@{B}hang@{UB}:  To repeat a useless program step endlessly.  Often caused by
improper programming techniques.  @{I}Warning:@{UI}  A program that hangs may leave
trashed data!  Always save whatever you can if a program hangs, then restart
the system.

	@{B}hard drive@{UB}:  A high-speed, large capacity drive with disks that are
not generally removed.  @{I}See drive.@{UI}

	@{B}HardFile@{UB}:  A large file which, via special handling, appears to DOS
to be a hard drive.

	@{B}headers@{UB}:  Information at the beginning of a file that tells the
system or a program how to handle the file--usually indicating the contents
of the file.

                                  @{B}I@{UB}

	@{B}I/O@{UB}:  Input/Output.  Term for data, or the process of transferring
data.

	@{B}icon@{UB}:  An image which represents an item on Workbench or desktop.

	@{B}iconify@{UB}:  Reduce control of a program to an image which, when
activated, will return control of the program to normal.

	@{B}ID@{UB}:  Identification.  A value that represents a specific device to a
controller or a specific type of file to a FileSystem.

	@{B}installation@{UB}:  A process whereby program files are stored and
configured for a user's specific system.

	@{B}installer@{UB}:  A program that unifies the process of installation
between one program and another.  The Amiga's installer works the same way
for any given program, but is flexible enough for most installation
procedures.

	@{B}interface@{UB}:  The method used to communicate with the program.  This
term often refers to the way devices communicate with the computer, but it
can also mean the way a user communicates with the computer.

	@{B}interrupt@{UB}:  A signal to the CPU from the hardware that an event has
occurred which may require processing.

	@{B}Intuition@{UB}:  The Amiga's system program which controls most
communications between the user and programs.

                                  @{B}K@{UB}

	@{B}kilobyte@{UB}:  1,024 bytes.  Often abbreviated as "K."  @{I}See byte.@{UI}

                                  @{B}M@{UB}

	@{B}Mac@{UB}:  Short for Macintosh.

	@{B}megabyte@{UB}:  1,024 kilobytes.  Often abbreviated as "meg."

	@{B}MMU@{UB}:  Memory Management Unit.  Special part of some CPU's that allow
extended software control of the computer's memory.

	@{B}monitor@{UB}:  A device that can display video images.

	@{B}MountList@{UB}:  A list of drivers and specifications of their respective
drives.  @{I}See DOSDriver.@{UI}

	@{B}multitask@{UB}:  A method of allowing more than one task to run within a
short period of time.

                                  @{B}O@{UB}

	@{B}optimize@{UB}:  Defragment.  @{I}See fragment.@{UI}  Also refers to a process
wherein unnecessary steps are removed from a procedure or a program.

	@{B}OS@{UB}:  Operating System.  The combined package of system software,
controlling all the aspects of the computer's system.

                                  @{B}P@{UB}

	@{B}parallel port@{UB}:  An interface which sends data 8 bits at a time.
@{I}See serial port.@{UI}

	@{B}partition@{UB}:  A section of a hard drive which is treated by the system
like a separate hard drive.

	@{B}patch@{UB}:  Special code and/or data designed to fix a problem with the
original code.

	@{B}PD@{UB}:  Public Domain.  Software not intended for sale or trade.

	@{B}peripherals@{UB}:  Devices which are usually connected to the computer
and controlled by the computer's system.

	@{B}platform@{UB}:  A complete set of hardware and software rules which
govern how the system software operates.  @{I}See OS.@{UI}

	@{B}priority@{UB}:  The level at which a task would need to be in order to
pre-empt your task.  In general, higher priority tasks can pre-empt lower
priority tasks, causing the lower tasks to go slower or even come to a
complete stop, briefly.

	@{B}process@{UB}:  (run by DOS) Refers to a special task which can
communicate with DOS.

	@{B}processor@{UB}, @{I}See CPU.@{UI}

                                  @{B}R@{UB}

	@{B}RAM@{UB}:  Random Access Memory.  Temporary, fast storage that programs
use for processing information.

	@{B}reboot@{UB}:  This clears most of the memory and returns the computer to
a state much like when it powered up.

	@{B}refresh@{UB}:  A method by which data is restored or changed.  This term
usually refers to the video image information.

	@{B}requester@{UB}:  A small window that usually appears within its
respective window, which contains information for the user and usually waits
for a response from the user.

	@{B}Restart@{UB}:  Mac equivalent of a reboot.  Clears memory and returns the
computer to an initial state.  In the case of the emulation, however, only
the Mac emulation is affected.  The Amiga is still in the exact same state
as before.

	@{B}ROM@{UB}:  Read-Only Memory.  Chips that contain unchangeable information
--usually in the form of code.  @{I}See code.@{UI}

                                  @{B}S@{UB}

	@{B}scroll@{UB}:  Document or figure which only partially appears in a
window, allowing you to move the window in respect to the image--which
usually means moving the data in the reverse direction and leaving the
window in the same place.

	@{B}SCSI@{UB}:  Small Computer System Interface.  (Usually pronounced
"Scuzzy.")  A system by which devices can communicate with the computer.

	@{B}serial port@{UB}:  An interface that sends 1 bit at a time to a device.
@{I}See parallel port.@{UI}

	@{B}SHIFT-Click@{UB}:  Holding either SHIFT key and using the mouse to
select and entry by clicking the mouse button.

	@{B}ShutDown@{UB}:  The Mac equivalent of turning the power off.

	@{B}storage@{UB}:  A method by which information can be retained for future
use.

	@{B}supervisor@{UB}:  A special CPU mode that allows any instructions to be
executed.

	@{B}SYBIL@{UB}:  A special pair of hardware adaptors that can be used to
control the rate at which data is read from or written to a floppy drive.

	@{B}system@{UB}:  The software which governs how most programs operate on any
given computer.

                                  @{B}T@{UB}

	@{B}task@{UB}:  A single program which usually serves one purpose.

	@{B}transfer@{UB}:  Input/output.  @{I}See I/O.@{UI}

	@{B}trash@{UB}:  A special icon where you can drag other icons to dispose of
them.  For Macs, device icons dropped over this icon are ejected, as well.

                                 @{B}V,Z@{UB}

	@{B}volume@{UB}:  Refers to a device or a name given to a specific directory
where files may be retrieved or stored.

	@{B}Zorro@{UB}:  Refers to the type of expansion slots used on the Amiga.
@ENDNODE Glossary
